**Shikwa** is chapter 20 of *Bang-E-Dara Part 3* (`allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8`). The entire poem is a direct address to God, but the most concentrated and explicit complaint about Muslims' fate appears across three adjacent stanzas:

**p-20fc7c** — the pivot verse, contrasting God's treatment of non-believers vs. Muslims:
> *"But all Your blessings fall upon the houses of the foe, / While on the wretched Muslims falls the lightning's fiery blow."*

**p-c09121** — the speaker reports that idols in temples gloat at Muslim decline, then challenges God directly:
> *"The unbelievers mock us now—do You feel this or not? / The Creed of Your own Oneness—have You utterly forgot?"*

**p-d1e7fe** — the most accusatory verse, demanding an explanation:
> *"Why is the wealth of this world now so scarce for Muslim hands? / Your power is the one that has no limits, no demands. / … We face the taunts of strangers, disgrace, and poverty; / Is this the prize for those who gave their very lives for Thee?"*

These three stanzas together form the poem's central grievance: Muslims sacrificed everything in God's service, yet now suffer while non-believers prosper—a divine injustice the speaker boldly names to God's face.
